\b Q. Function of Sync (1 beat), Sync (2 beats), Sync (1 beat) etc. These mods are on both drop-down lists on the Names and Ranges box in the Zones page. (I at first assumed that setting a sample to sync 1 beat would make it just play once per beat, etc, but it just plays as usual when I press down a key. In addition: Does the first of these two drop-down mod lists on the Names and Ranges box apply to the keyrange? Does the second apply to pitch? How is this supposed to work? Are there other things people are doing with it?\b0\par
\par
\cf1\b A.\b0  The ranges are a condition which if met will let the note play when you press the key. It won't trigger any more notes than you play, it just filters the ones out where the conditions aren't met. Basically it's just like key & velocity, the sample plays when it's in the range, except that you can choose the source yourself.\par
An example usage would be to use the modwheel to trigger a sample with vibrato when it's above 64 and a normal one when not. Put them on the same key and set the additional ranges to:\par
\par
non vibrato-sample - [ 0 ][ modwheel ][ 63 ]\par
vibrato-sample - [ 64 ][ modwheel ][ 127 ]\par
\par
The sync ones are the same, except that they depend on the song position. So you could for example let a key play open hihats on the last half of the beat  and closed ones on the first.\par
\par
One way to use it:\par
A drummer is using one trigger besides his acoustic kit. So while he hits the trigger Shortcircuit would decide in dependance of the Songposition wich sample is to play. (open Hihat & closed Hihat - or - snare & sound fx...)\par
