\b Q. Sometimes when i load my DAW project file with SC1 in it i would get a message that SC1 can't find a particular sample and am promted for manual navigating to the location the missing sample is stored at. How can I overcome this behavior?\par
\b0\par
\cf1\b A.\b0  Instead of saving SC1 instruments and multis in its proprietary format, try saving its settings to a plugin preset in the proprietary format of your DAW, just like you do with the majority of VST instruments. In cases of many DAWs this will make the SC1 insrument saved thereby non-transferable to another DAW, so if you intend to do it, save the instrument in SC1 proprietary format.\par
\par
Or you may run scmPathReplace.vbs courtesy of user \i qwanta  \cf0\i0 (included with this Q &A in folder 'Shortcircuit patch sample path problem workaround' )\i\par
\cf1\i0\par
Basically, if you put this script in the same directory as one or more scm files and run it (double-click it), it will cycle through them and replace all occurrences of $relative with the current folder path. So if you do a save multi+samples, all your sample paths now contain the dreaded $relative variable (which doesn't work as we know, causing the need to manually navigate to the location of the samples when a project is loaded).\par
Now, stick the vbs script in the scm folder, run it - this replaces $relative with the absolute path -, reload the scm into your shortcircuit instance and you have now absolute file references.\par
\par
\pard{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf2\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\nowidctlpar\fi-720\li720 1) save multi+samples\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}2) run script\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}3) reload scm\par
{\pntext\f2\'B7\tab}4) save host project\par
