\cf1\b A.\b0  It like a lowpass filter for control data. It will smooth out the control data to make fast changes slow.\par
One typical use for this would be to prevent stepping from the midi-controllers, but SC does this in a more clever way already. It can be good if you want the controller intentionally slow though.\cf0\par
\par
\cf1 they're useful for controlling the timing of filter sweeps.\par
\par
For example: a low pass filter opens to let a pad through on a track - the low pass filter goes from 100% closed to 100% open. Instead of setting up a complex controller curve in the sequencer to control the filter, I just enter a square wave (controller 0->127), then in sc send the controller->lag 1, lag 1->filter cutoff, and then adjust the lag 1 time to control how fast the filter opens.\par
\par
another use is slowing down aftertouch response. Aftertouch tends to be hyper-sensitive on many keyboards, so if you want to make precise yet drastic changes with it, the Lag Generators are perfect.\par
\par
if you have this modulation routing:\par
\par
\par
[modwheel] [+2.0oct] [f1:cutoff]\par
\par
and want the control to move slower/smoother, insert a lag generator like this:\par
\par
\par
[modwheel] [+100.0%] [lag 1    ]\par
[lag 1   ] [+2.0oct] [f1:cutoff]\par
\par
